= auto-session-timeout

Provides automatic session timeout in a Rails application.

== Installation

Install the gem directly:

  sudo gem install pelargir-auto-session-timeout --source=http://gems.github.com
  
Or install the gem in your Rails project:
  
  script/plugin install git://github.com/pelargir/auto-session-timeout.git

Or clone the project:

  git clone git://github.com/pelargir/auto-session-timeout.git

== Usage

After installing, tell your application controller to use auto timeout:

  class ApplicationController < ActionController::Base
    auto_session_timeout 1.hour
    ...
  end

You will also need to insert this line inside the <body></body> tags in
your views. The easiest way to do this is to insert it once inside your
default or application-wide layout:

  <html>
    <head>...</head>
    <body>
      <%= auto_session_timeout_js %>
      ...
    </body>
  </html>

Last, you need to setup an action to return the session status. Define
an action in a controller (the best choice is probably your user or session
controller). The action should look like this:

  class SessionsController < ApplicationController
    def active
     render_auto_session_timeout
    end
    ...
  end

Make sure to add this line in routes.rb to map "/active" to this action:

  map.active '/active', :controller => 'sessions', :action => 'active'

You're done! By default, sessions auto timeout after 60 minutes of inactivity.
This value will be configurable in future versions of the plugin.

